      "acceptanceCriteria": "FEA software used under documented QMS with version control; solver validation reports available from vendor.",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical 2022 R2 used under DePuy Synthes QMS with ISO 13485 controls. FDA in-house solver (Abaqus 2021) operated under CDRH software QA procedures. Version control, change management, and regression test records available for both platforms. Achieved level 2: documented QA procedures with evidence of execution."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Solver benchmark problems demonstrate correct implementation of contact mechanics and large-deformation plasticity relevant to pedicle screw bending.",
      "rationale": "Both Ansys and Abaqus verified against NAFEMS benchmark set LE1/LE10 and vendor-supplied contact patch test. Nonlinear material and geometric nonlinearity benchmarks confirmed. Achieved level 2: standard benchmark suite completed with documented pass/fail records."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study demonstrates <5% change in all three QoIs between successive refinement levels; Richardson extrapolation applied.",
      "rationale": "Three-level mesh refinement study performed on screw shank and thread root regions (coarse: 0.8 mm, medium: 0.4 mm, fine: 0.2 mm global element size). Richardson extrapolation applied; GCI values <2.1% for stiffness, <3.4% for yield force, <4.7% for force at 40 mm. Achieved level 3: formal convergence study with extrapolation and GCI reporting."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Solver residuals monitored; time-step sensitivity confirmed; contact stabilization energy <1% of total strain energy.",
      "rationale": "Force and displacement residuals converged to <1e-5 norm. Augmented Lagrange contact formulation used; contact stabilization energy monitored and confirmed <0.8% of total internal energy at all load steps. Load-step sensitivity study confirmed results independent of increment size. Achieved level 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Independent analyst review of model setup; boundary condition and loading application verified against ASTM F1717 protocol.",
      "rationale": "Model setup independently reviewed by second analyst at each institution. Boundary conditions (fixed distal block, actuator displacement applied at proximal block centroid) verified against ASTM F1717-15 Section 8. Material assignment and contact pair definition reviewed via checklist. Achieved level 2: independent peer review with documented sign-off."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Constitutive model selection justified by material characterization data; contact formulation appropriate for screw-rod interface behavior.",
      "rationale": "Bilinear isotropic hardening model calibrated to Ti-6Al-4V ELI tensile coupon data (n=5 per lot). Elastic modulus 114 GPa, yield strength 880 MPa, tangent modulus 2.1 GPa confirmed against ASTM F136 material certificates. Coulomb friction coefficient 0.2 at screw-rod interface based on published tribology data for titanium-on-titanium. Model form uncertainty assessed as low given well-characterized material and simple contact geometry. Achieved level 3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "All geometric and material inputs traceable to measured values; input uncertainty propagated through sensitivity analysis.",
      "rationale": "Screw geometry inputs derived from CMM measurements of production screws (n=5); rod geometry from vendor drawings with dimensional inspection records. Material properties from certified material test reports. One-at-a-time sensitivity analysis performed for modulus (±5%), yield strength (±3%), and friction coefficient (±50%). Stiffness QoI sensitivity to friction coefficient <1%; yield force sensitivity to yield strength ±2.9%. Achieved level 3: traceable inputs with documented sensitivity analysis."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "N≥10 test constructs from production lots; lot traceability documented; dimensional inspection confirms conformance to design intent.",
      "rationale": "N=11 non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs tested across two laboratories (n=6 Lab A, n=5 Lab B). All constructs from production lots with full material and dimensional traceability. CMM inspection of representative screws confirmed thread form and shank diameter within drawing tolerances. Inter-laboratory sample equivalence confirmed by t-test (p=0.43 for stiffness). Achieved level 3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions span the range of clinically relevant loading scenarios; at minimum two distinct test configurations evaluated.",
      "rationale": "Testing performed under a single ASTM F1717 static compression-bending configuration only. Dynamic fatigue and torsional loading conditions not evaluated in this validation activity. This represents a known gap: the achieved level (2) is below the required level (3) for this factor. The gap is accepted based on the regulatory precedent that static compression-bending is the primary FDA-required test for pedicle screw constructs, and the modeling team has committed to supplemental dynamic validation in a subsequent COU."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model inputs matched to experimental specimen measurements; any deviations from nominal geometry quantified and their effect on QoIs assessed.",
      "rationale": "FEA model geometry updated to reflect CMM-measured screw dimensions for each laboratory lot. Torque applied to set screws in FEA matched to experimental protocol (4 Nm ± 0.2 Nm). Polyaxial screw head angle set to 0° in both model and experiment. Material properties matched to certified test reports for the specific production lot used in testing. Residual geometric deviations <0.05 mm assessed as having <1% effect on all QoIs via perturbation analysis. Achieved level 3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric (percent difference and E/uval) applied to all three QoIs; acceptance bounds pre-specified prior to unblinding.",
      "rationale": "Pre-specified acceptance bounds (<10% percent difference, E/uval < 1.96) documented in validation plan prior to experimental data unblinding. All three QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm) compared using both metrics. Results: stiffness 2.1%/0.62, yield force 4.7%/0.91, force at 40 mm 6.2%/1.44. All within bounds. Achieved level 3: pre-specified quantitative comparison with documented unblinding protocol."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs directly map to clinical performance endpoints or regulatory submission requirements; linkage documented.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness relates to load-sharing with the vertebral column and adjacent segment stress. Yield force is the primary structural integrity endpoint for regulatory review. Force at 40 mm displacement characterizes post-yield energy absorption relevant to fracture risk assessment. All three QoIs are explicitly required by FDA guidance on pedicle screw testing submissions. Linkage between QoIs and clinical endpoints documented in the validation plan. Achieved level 3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation scenario matches COU geometry, loading, and boundary conditions; any differences between validation and COU scenarios assessed for their impact on model credibility.",
      "rationale": "Validation activity directly replicates the COU scenario: same screw design (non-cannulated 7.5 mm), same test standard (ASTM F1717), same loading mode (static compression-bending), same QoIs. No extrapolation beyond the validated scenario is claimed in this COU. The single test condition gap (Test conditions factor) is the only identified deviation between validation and COU scope. Achieved level 3 for relevance given direct correspondence between validation and intended use scenario."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/nagaraja-cou1-noncannulated-decision",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/nagaraja-credibility-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "All 13 V&V 40 credibility factors assessed. Twelve of thirteen factors meet or exceed required levels. One factor (Test conditions) achieves level 2 against a required level of 3 due to the single-condition ASTM F1717 static test protocol; this gap is accepted given regulatory precedent and the commitment to supplemental dynamic validation. All three QoIs pass pre-specified quantitative acceptance bounds. The overall credibility profile supports an assurance level of Medium, consistent with the Medium model influence and Medium decision consequence of this COU. The package is accepted for regulatory submission purposes. Note: the force-at-40mm validation result characterizes aleatory variability qualitatively via narrative description of inter-specimen scatter; a formal structured UQ node was not linked to that result, which represents a documentation gap identified post-review.",
